---
import { Card, CardContent, CardDescription, CardHeader, CardTitle } from "@/components/ui/card";
import SiteLayout from "@/layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="Privacy Policy · pkgs.ml"
  description="Privacy policy for pkgs.ml"
>
  <section class="mx-auto w-full max-w-6xl px-4 py-6 sm:px-6">
    <div class="grid gap-4">
      <nav class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
        <a href="/" class="hover:text-foreground">All packages</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <span class="text-foreground">privacy</span>
      </nav>

      <Card className="rounded-md shadow-none">
        <CardHeader className="border-b border-border">
          <CardTitle className="text-base">Privacy Policy</CardTitle>
          <CardDescription>
            How pkgs.ml handles identity, package metadata, and publish credentials.
          </CardDescription>
        </CardHeader>
        <CardContent className="grid gap-6 py-4 text-base leading-7 text-muted-foreground">
          <section class="grid gap-2">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">Data minimization</h2>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml is designed to keep as little personal data as possible. We do not keep
              generic per-request logs, and we do not intentionally store raw IP addresses in the
              registry database.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-2">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">GitHub login</h2>
            <p>
              When you sign in with GitHub, pkgs.ml stores your GitHub login, GitHub user id,
              display name when available, and avatar URL. This data is used to create your pkgs.ml
              account, associate package ownership, and show your identity in the web interface.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-2">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">Sessions and cookies</h2>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml uses a secure session cookie to keep you signed in. The cookie is scoped to
              the pkgs.ml domain and is used only for authentication and account actions such as
              managing publish tokens.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-2">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">Publish tokens</h2>
            <p>
              Publish tokens are shown in plaintext exactly once when created. After creation,
              pkgs.ml stores only a derived hash plus token metadata such as name, capabilities,
              creation time, last-used time, and revocation time.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-2">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">Published package metadata</h2>
            <p>
              Packages published to pkgs.ml expose public metadata such as package name, version,
              description, license, categories, dependencies, owners, and source repository links.
              This information is used to build package pages, search results, and index documents.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-2">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">Operational and product events</h2>
            <p>
              The registry records specific events that are needed to operate the service, such as
              package publication, indexing, token creation, and other package-registry lifecycle
              actions. These event records are tied to the action itself rather than acting as a
              generic log of every request.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-2">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">Downloads and analytics</h2>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml may record package downloads, index reads, search queries, and page views in
              purpose-built analytics tables so the ecosystem can expose aggregate statistics. These
              metrics are intended to be anonymous and aggregated. We do not want or need raw IP
              address tracking for package-registry analytics.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-2">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">What we do not store by default</h2>
            <p>
              We do not treat generic request logging as a product feature. The default direction of
              the service is to avoid storing raw request histories, raw IP addresses, or unrelated
              browsing metadata unless a future feature requires a narrowly scoped and documented
              exception.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-2">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">Changes</h2>
            <p>
              This policy is an initial draft and will evolve as pkgs.ml grows. Material changes
              should be published on this page before they take effect.
            </p>
          </section>
        </CardContent>
      </Card>
    </div>
  </section>
</SiteLayout>
